data.text: main ♦ major ♦ key ♦ central ♦ principal ♦ chief ♦ prime

data.chText: 以上各词均用以形容主要的、最重要的人或事物。
data.enText: These words all describe sb/sth that is the largest or most important of its kind.
main
[only before noun] largest or most important
Be careful crossing the main road.

data.chText: 最重要的是要保持冷静。
data.enText: The main thing is to remain calm.
major
[usually before noun] very large or important

data.chText: 他在建立这个系统的过程中扮演了主要的角色。
data.enText: He played a major role in setting up the system.

data.chText: major最常用于不定冠词a之后，与单数名词连用；或不用冠词，与复数名词连用。major与the或my/your/his/her/our/their连用时意为最主要的、最重要的：
data.enText: Major is most often used after a with a singular noun, or no article with a plural noun. When it is used with the or my/your/his/her/our/their it means ‘the largest or most important’.

data.chText: 在这里我们最关心的是解决贫穷问题。
data.enText: Our major concern here is combatting poverty.

data.chText: 在该含义中major只用以指人的想法或担忧，而非物质的东西，且较main正式：
data.enText: In this meaning it is only used to talk about ideas or worries that people have, not physical things, and it is also more formal than main .
Be careful crossing the major road.
The major thing is to remain calm.
key

data.chText: 指最重要的、主要的、关键的：
data.enText: [usually before noun] most important; essential

data.chText: 他是这场运动的关键人物。
data.enText: He was a key figure in the campaign.

data.chText: key最常用于商务和政治语境，可用以指想法或某人在某情势下起的作用，而非物质的东西。key较major稍非正式，用于名词加连系动词后尤其如此：
data.enText: Key is used most frequently in business and political contexts. It can be used to talk about ideas, or the part that sb plays in a situation, but not physical things. It is slightly more informal than major , especially when used after a noun and linking verb.

data.chText: 在这个时候速度是关键。
data.enText: Speed is key at this point.
central

data.chText: 指最重要的、首要的、主要的：
data.enText: ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 最重要的问题是种族主义泛滥。
data.enText: The central issue is that of widespread racism.

data.chText: central与key用法相似，但更正式，最常用于be central to短语中。
data.enText: Central is used in a similar way to key , but is more formal. It is most frequently used in the phrase sth is central to sth else .
principal
[only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 跳过它的主要原因是时间不足。
data.enText: The principal reason for this omission is lack of time.

data.chText: principal主要用于陈述无可争辩的事实。表明意见或说服别人相信你所见到的事实，较常用key或central：
data.enText: Principal is mostly used for statements of fact about which there can be no argument. To state an opinion, or to try to persuade sb of the facts as you see them, it is more usual to use key or central .
The key/central issue here is …
chief

data.chText: 指最重要的、首要的、主要的：
data.enText: [only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 失业是贫穷的主要原因。
data.enText: Unemployment was the chief cause of poverty.
prime
[only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important; to be considered first

data.chText: 我最关心的是保护自己的财产。
data.enText: My prime concern is to protect my property.

value.def: You use major when you want to describe something that is more important, serious, or significant than other things in a group or situation.

example.ex: The major factor in the decision to stay or to leave was usually professional...
example.tran: 职业上的考虑往往是决定去留的主要因素。

example.ex: Drug abuse has long been a major problem for the authorities there...
example.tran: 长久以来，吸毒一直是那里的当局面临的一个大难题。

example.ex: Exercise has a major part to play in preventing and combating disease.
example.tran: 体育锻炼在疾病防治方面发挥着重要作用。

value.tran: 较重要的;较重大的;主要的

value.def: A major is an officer who is one rank above captain in the British army or the United States army, air force, or marines.

example.ex: I was a major in the war, you know.
example.tran: 你知道，战争期间我是一名陆军少校。

value.tran: (英国)陆军(或海军陆战队)少校;(美国)陆军(或空军、海军陆战队)少校

value.def: At a university or college in the United States, a student's major is the main subject that they are studying.

example.ex: English majors would be asked to explore the roots of language.
example.tran: 英语专业的学生会被要求探究语言的根源。

value.tran: (美国大学中的)主修课程，专业

value.def: At a university or college in the United States, if a student is, for example, a geology major, geology is the main subject they are studying.

example.ex: She was named the outstanding undergraduate history major at the University of Oklahoma.
example.tran: 她被评选为俄克拉何马大学历史专业的优等生。

value.tran: (美国大学中)主修…的学生，…专业的学生

value.def: If a student at a university or college in the United States majors in a particular subject, that subject is the main one they study.

example.ex: He majored in finance at Claremont Men's College in California.
example.tran: 他在加利福尼亚州的克莱尔蒙特男子学院主修金融专业。

value.def: In music, a major scale is one in which the third note is two tones higher than the first.

example.tran: 莫扎特D大调第35号交响曲

value.def: A major is a large or important company.

example.ex: Oil majors need not fear being unable to sell their crude.
example.tran: 大型石油公司无需担心原油销售不出去。

value.def: The majors are groups of professional sports teams that compete against each other, especially in American baseball.

example.ex: I knew what I could do in the minor leagues, I just wanted a chance to prove myself in the majors.
example.tran: 我知道自己在职业棒球小联合会中实力如何，我只是想有个机会能在职业棒球大联盟中证明一下自己。

value.tran: 职业体育总会;(尤指美国)职业棒球联合总会，职业棒球大联盟

value.def: A major is an important sporting competition, especially in golf or tennis.

example.ex: Sarazen became the first golfer to win all four majors.
example.tran: 萨拉岑成为了首位高尔夫四大满贯赛冠军。

value.tran: 大型体育比赛;(尤指高尔夫球或网球)大赛
